ARTICLE.TITLE: Willerby Caravans making job cuts which will 'affect many families'
ARTICLE.TEXT:
Sign up to the Hull Live newsletter for daily updates and breaking news Sign up here! Thank you for subscribing See our privacy notice Invalid Email

Employees at Willerby Caravans have been told their jobs could be at risk as a result of the Covid-19 pandemic.

The caravan industry has been hit hard by the pandemic and the subsequent lockdown, with the National Caravan Council (NCC) saying the sector had lost the majority of its 2020 sales so far.

Last month, Hull's three MPs spoke with Business Minister Nadhim Zahawi in a bid to save the region's caravan industry, warning afterwards that the industry was not yet "out of the woods".

In a letter sent to Willerby Caravans employees this week, CEO Peter Munk told his staff that job cuts were on the way.

He said: "Today we are announcing the formal process to start consultation on a number of changes to reduce our overall cost base and prepare the company to weather any future shocks to the UK economy in general as well as our seasonal industry.

"These proposed changes will impact many areas and levels of the business that are covered by salaried month staff.

"The hourly weekly paid staff will not be part of these changes and consultation."

He said the changes had been driven by three factors: the unprecedented economic uncertainty caused by the Covid-19 pandemic; the new ways of working that had been adapted during lockdown, and the imminent implementation of a company-wide ERP system.

Watch: The latest coronavirus news headlines

Video Loading Video Unavailable Click to play Tap to play The video will start in 8 Cancel Play now

He added: "The decision to start this formal consultation process has not been taken lightly as we know this will impact many individuals and families, but we also have an obligation to ensure that Willerby can come through these uncertain times a better and stronger company.

"We will go through the process in a fair and professional manner and will ask everyone to do the same and respect each individual and the ultimate decisions the same way."

He concluded by saying those who would be impacted had already been approached, adding that the expected completion date for the consultation period was September 23, with final announcements to be made soon after that date.

Find local issues reported in your area

In a statement to Hull Live, Mr Munk said: "We can confirm that we have entered into a period of consultation with a number of our salaried employees.

"Those staff who have been identified as being within the group that is at risk have all been spoken to and we will continue to communicate and support them throughout the process.

"No hourly paid employees are part of these changes or consultation process."
